-- PPC, Coronation, Illovo and Tongaat May Move: South African Equity Preview
-- B y   S i k o n a t h i   M a n t s h a n t s h a   a n d   R e n e e   B o n o r c h i s
-- 2010-11-09T05:56:53Z
-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2010-11-08/ppc-coronation-illovo-and-tongaat-may-move-south-african-equity-preview.html
The following is a list of companies
whose shares may have unusual price changes in South Africa.
Stock symbols are in parentheses after company names and prices
are from the last close.  South Africa’s  FTSE/JSE Africa All Share Index  lost 67.48,
or 0.2 percent, to 31,388.98 at the 5 p.m. close of trading in
Johannesburg.  Anglo American Plc  (AGL SJ): De Beers, in which Anglo has a
45 percent stake, said diamond demand will rise 20 percent a
year in India and China with half of global growth coming from
the two nations within the next few years. Shares in Anglo fell
4.85 rand, or 1.5 percent, to 328.64 rand.  Coronation Fund Managers Ltd.  (CML SJ): The Cape Town-based
money manager said full-year earnings excluding one-time items
jumped 112 percent while assets under management rose 28
percent. Shares in Coronation gained 47 cents, or 3 percent, to
16.30 rand.  Illovo Sugar Ltd.  (ILV SJ):  The South African Sugar
Association , which represents producers, is scheduled to release
an output forecast. Illovo, Africa’s largest producer of the
sweetener, fell 29 cents, or 1.1 percent, to 27 rand. Shares in
 Tongaat Hulett Ltd.  (TON SJ), the second-biggest producer, rose
1.45 rand, or 1.4 percent, to 103.45 rand.  Pretoria Portland Cement Company Ltd.  (PPC SJ): South
Africa’s largest producer of the building material said full-
year net income fell 1 percent to 1.01 billion rand ($147
million) from a year earlier. Shares in PPC were unchanged at
34.30 rand.  Purple Capital Ltd.  (PPE SJ): The company with investments
in finance and asset-management firms said its loss for the 12
months through August narrowed to 50.5 million rand from 88.4
million rand a year earlier. Shares in Purple added 1 cent, or
4.6 percent, to 23 cents.  Sasol Ltd.  (SOL SJ): Oil fell for the first time in seven
days in New York as analysts forecast U.S. crude inventories
climbed to the highest in 18 months and a strengthening dollar
cut the appeal of commodities. Sasol, the world’s biggest maker
of motor fuel from coal, gained 4.91 rand, or 1.5 percent, to
334.01 rand.  Shoprite Holdings Ltd.  (SHP SJ): South Africa’s largest
retailer by market value is being investigated by Zambian
competition authorities, Business Day reported, citing Chilufya
Sampa, the Zambian Competition Commission’s director of mergers
and monopolies. Shares in Shoprite fell 41 cents, or 0.4
percent, to 102.39 rand.  Shares or American depositary receipts of South African
companies closed as follows:  Anglo American Plc (AAUKY US) fell 2.3 percent to $23.93.
AngloGold Ashanti Ltd. (AU US) rose 1.3 percent to $49.93. BHP
Billiton Ltd. (BBL US) dropped 1.2 percent to $79.01. DRDGold
Ltd. (DROOY US) gained 0.8 percent to $4.98. Gold Fields Ltd.
(GFI US) climbed 2.2 percent to $17.23. Harmony Gold Mining Co.
(HMY US) added 1.3 percent to $12.51. Impala Platinum Holdings
(IMPUY US) was largely unchanged at $30.51. Sappi Ltd. (SPP US)
rose 5.3 percent to $5.19. Sasol Ltd. (SSL US) added 0.9 percent
to $48.87.  To contact the reporters on this story:
